idCitation.resTitle: CMAP's ON TO 2050 Forecast of Population, Households, and Employment by Local Allocation Zone (LAZ)

dataIdInfo.idPurp: GIS shapefile representing small-area CMAP forecasts of population, households and employment, with base-year (2015) estimates and projections at five-year intervals to the year 2050. Released in conjunction with CMAP's ON TO 2050 regional comprehensive plan in October, 2018.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This shapefile provides base-year (2015) estimates and projections at five-year intervals to the year 2050 of total Households, Population Living in Households, and Total Wage and Salary Employment.

The unit of geography is the Local Allocation Zone, or "LAZ," which are CMAP travel model subzones (roughly equivalent to PLSS quarter-sections) subdivided by 2010 municipal (Census) boundaries and Chicago Community Areas. This composite geography was developed so that the data could be summarized to more recognizable geographic levels, while still performing its primary role as the source of trip generation estimation in the travel model. NOTE: These projections are the result of modeling procedures which incorporate a number of factors represented at a variety of scales; as such, they cannot be considered precise at any specific location. These data are only appropriate for planning purposes when aggregated to larger areas.

The spatial extent of this dataset is the seven counties within the CMAP region: Cook, DuPage, Kane, Kendall, Lake, McHenry, and Will.

For more information on the 2050 forecast, please see the ON TO 2050 Plan appendix "ON TO 2050 Socioeconomic Forecast," in particular Part 2, "Local Area Allocation."

Unique sub-county geographic identifier that distinguishes between incorporated and unincorporated jurisdictions; this includes a subdivision of the City of Chicago into the 77 Community Areas. Municipalities (except for the City of Chicago) are represented by the five-digit Census Place FIPS code. Unincorporated portions of townships are represented by the five-digit Census Minor Civil Division FIPS code. Chicago Community Areas are represented by the standard 77 Community Area designations originally developed by the University of Chicago in the 1920's. To maintain five-digit consistency, these are represented as "14x" plus the two digit Community Area code.

CMAP Travel Model Subzone ID. Subzones are the smallest unit of geography in CMAP's travel demand models, and roughly equate to PLSS quarter-sections. This release is based on the "2009" version of the travel model zone scheme.
